04983nam a22006855i 9780271085715DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20212019pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710857157 a10.1515/97802710857152doi  a(DE-B1597)584220  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aLIT0060002bisacsh00aJustification and Emancipation :bThe Critical Theory of Rainer Forst /ced. by Amy Allen, Eduardo Mendieta. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPenn State Series in Critical Theory ;v200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tChapter 1 Introduction -- tChapter 2 The Justification of Progress and the Progress of Justification -- tChapter 3 Autonomy and Justification What Reasons Do We Owe Each Other and Ourselves? -- tChapter 4 Objectionable Objections On Toleration, Respect, and Esteem -- tChapter 5 The Right to Justification and the Good of Nonalienation -- tChapter 6 “A Certain Relation in the Space of Justifications” Intentions, Lateral Effects, and Rainer Forst’s Concept of Noumenal Power -- tChapter 7 Opening “Political Contexts of Injustice” -- tChapter 8 A Feminist Engagement with Forst’s Transnational Justice -- tChapter 9 Progress, Normativity, and Universality Reply to Forst -- tChapter 10 Navigating a World of Conflict and Power Reply to Critics -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis work is both an introduction to and a critical appraisal of the work of Rainer Forst, one of the most important political theorists in Germany today. Structured for classroom use, this collection of original essays engages with Forst’s extant corpus in ways that are both appreciative and critical.Forst is an original, prolific, and widely known member of the “fourth generation” of Frankfurt School theorists. His significant contributions include a Rawlsian-Habermasian conception of justice that takes seriously the dissent of citizens and moral agents; an original interpretation and analysis of the concept of toleration; and, most recently, a generative idea of “noumenal power,” to which every human being has a claim by virtue of their equal standing within the moral community of all rational beings. Opening with an essay by Forst on the normative conception of progress and closing with a reply to his critics, this volume is both a primer on and a window into the latest contributions to the tradition of critical theory.In addition to the editors, the contributors include John Christman, Mattias Iser, Catherine Lu, John P. McCormick, Sarah Clark Miller, and Melissa Yates.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh1 aAllen, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAllen, Amy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChristman, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForst, Rainer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIser, Mattias, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLu, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCormick, John P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMendieta, Eduardo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMendieta, Eduardo, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMiller, Sarah Clark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYates, Melissa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978027108571540uht